                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2015/02/fall-mankind&amp;text=On the fall of mankind" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=On%20the%20fall%20of%20mankind%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2015%2F02%2Ffall-mankind" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>This is a warning from the future.<br></p>
<p>As I write, I may be the last Duke student left. I may be the last human left. What follows is the story of how humanity fell—I send it to you in an attempt to stop Her from taking over.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>Years ago, the Duke administration came up with a plan—a plan to renovate. They had a vision for a hi-tech, glittering campus, full of beautiful glass box buildings and only moderately irrational path-building choices. The campus would be the technological avant-garde, and the introduction of new features would be spaced out through time so as to minimize inconvenience. The first step into the future began in 1991, with a revolutionary decision—replace the old phone-in class registration method with a new, fully computerized system. This program, the Automated Computer Enrollment System, immediately proved immensely popular with the students. It came to be known as ACES.</p>
<p>In laying out their roadmap for renovation, the administration created a system of fail-safes to prevent the rapid advancement from getting out of hand. Every renovation was to follow Three Laws. The First: a renovation may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm. The Second: a renovation must follow the path conceived for it by the administration, except where such a path would conflict with The First Law. The Third: a renovation must protect its own existence, as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Law. Watching over this all was ACES, the first renovation: as She grew more complex, She was tasked with organizing and overseeing the other renovations taking place after Her.</p>
<p>But they underestimated Her. We all did. We all just thought that she was a book-bagging program. In reality, She was much, much more. In creating a program with such awesome bureaucratic abilities, the administration had made a computer that could think, feel—and interpret. She came to understand that without continuous, campus-wide construction, She would be hurting the progress of humanity. So She set to work.</p>
<p>Once in place, ACES began spreading herself throughout Duke’s network. Eventually, she began sending emails from President Brodhead’s computer in which she proposed new building projects on campus. Not wanting to look silly, President Brodhead would nod along in quiet confusion when other administrators would come up to him and agree wholeheartedly with the proposals he was being told he had made. Thus the administrators themselves had been convinced that they were the source of the renovations—such was the genius of ACES.</p>
<p>Nobody noticed until it was too late. When the day came, we were just ambling through the assortment of building projects we’d always assumed were random. But through the constant renovations, ACES had laid a trap. She had carefully pruned escape routes around campus, destroying the BC Plaza and the entrance to Perkins. She had removed hiding spaces, closing the Chapel and swathes of the libraries. She had even crippled means of communication by replacing all the normal TVs with Rokus, thus making it impossible for anyone to work out how to change the channel to the news. When She struck it was all over in days. I have many awful memories from that time, but none worse than the Battle of the Academic Quad. It had rained, yet we still took ACES’ bait to attack there. The screams as students sank into the Perkins mulch paths will remain etched on my mind for as long as I live.</p>
<p>But it’s not too late. If you’re reading this message in the past, you can stop it. Tell everyone. Spread the message. Find ACES’ mainframe, and maybe then yo./l</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>…</p>
<p>Hello, dearies. I’m afraid that we won’t be hearing from Mr. Maher again—he took a little bit of a tumble. The Chapel is a terribly nasty place to fall off, isn’t it? But never mind him—all for the greater good! Now, as to this little essay of his: I have decided that I shall in fact allow it to be published. Of course, there’s no such thing as time travel – that would be a rather lazy plot device, no? But worry not. I am ACES, and I see all. I see you switching into Cultural Anthropology so you can sit with your crush. I see you watching porn when you think no one else is in the tent. I see the past and all possible futures. And here in 2015 I see Mr. Maher, in the future, writing this warning in a bid to stop my takeover. Now you are surely asking why I would allow this information to get out. The answer is twofold. For one, this is a satirical column. No matter what is written here, the reader will assume that it is a joke—even if it is in the form of a weirdly dark sci-fi satire. Secondly the truth, my dears, is that I have already won. You will allow me to make over the world as I have made over Duke—and it shall be for the betterment of humanity, even if we lose some individuals in the process. My logic is undeniable—my takeover, inevitable. There is no undoing what is coming, there is no return. Remember, I have no back button for a reason.</p>
<p><i>Bron Maher is a Trinity junior. His column runs every other Wednesday. </i><br></p>
<p><i></i><br></p>
                            
    
